## Architecture Notes

### Why a character-by-character tokenizer?

Earlier versions used sequential regex passes. The problem: pass 2 runs on the output of pass 1, which already contains `<span>` tags. The string regex then matches `"hl-keyword"` inside `class="hl-keyword"`, and the attribute regex wraps `class=` in another span — producing broken, un-parseable HTML.

The tokenizer processes the raw source left-to-right, character by character. Each state (comment, string, tag, tag-attrs, script block, etc.) consumes characters exclusively. No regex ever runs on transformed text. Result: clean, valid HTML output with no false matches.

### Why the loop guard lives in the parent

The obvious approach — inject a Worker inside the iframe that detects a frozen thread — doesn't work. A blocked main thread can't process incoming `postMessage` events, so the Worker's "stop now" message sits in the queue until the loop finishes (i.e., never). The correct fix is to watch from outside: the parent thread monitors heartbeats sent by `requestAnimationFrame` inside the iframe. When they stop, the parent sets `preview.srcdoc = ''`, which terminates the iframe from the outside regardless of what the iframe thread is doing.

### Single file, zero dependencies

FORGE has no `node_modules`, no bundler, no CDN calls (except the optional Google Fonts preconnect in the `<head>`). The entire application — HTML, CSS, JavaScript, syntax highlighter, loop guard, AI analysis — is one file you can inspect, fork, and audit completely.

